	 - the Kriṅ named Landəp: 1 māṣa;
	- the Makudur who will move forward to pierce the ḍaṇḍər: 10 māṣas, 1 set of cloth, together with gifts i.e. equiped with offerings;
	- the Vadihati who will move forward to pierce the harava wood-pigeon: 10 māṣas, 1 set of cloth, together with gifts i.e. equiped with offerings.

‘Pay heed you gods at Śrī Haricandana, Agastya Mahārṣi, 
	- East, South, West, North, Center, Zenith, Nadir;
	- Sun, Moon, Earth, Water, Wind, Fire, Yajamāna, Ether;
	- Dharma, Day and Night, Twilight, Heart;
	- Yakṣas, Rākṣasas, Piśācas, Pretas, Asuras, Garuḍa, Gandharvas; 
	- Four Lokapālas: Yama, Varuṇa, Kubera, Vāsava Indra
	- And sons of the gods: Five Kuśikas, Nandīśvara, Mahākāla, Six Vināyakas, Snake-Kings, goddess Durgā
	- Quadrangular ones Aśvins?, Ananta, Surendra;
	- children of Kāla and Mṛtyu: Gaṇas and Bhūtas
	- you well-known ones who protect the palace of his majesty the king at Mḍaṁ in the land of Matarām
	- you who take part in embodying, entering in all bodies
	- you all who as witness watch far and near, at day and by night, as you listen to the agreement, the curse, the oath, the admission of us to all you gods:
	- if the bad man does not hold firm, does not safeguard that curse being deposited by the Vahuta Hyaṅ, the Kudur, Lord and servant, old and young, man and female, religious man and householder, as well as minister, Vahuta and headman,
	- whoever disturbs the varuk land at Ālasantan as Paṅurumbigyan freehold, bestowed by his majesty the king on the venerable Kabayān, mother of the lord minister of Halu called Dyah Sahasra, up to the future’s future may split asunder, all the more so if he shall uproot the holy sīma stone. Therefore, even if he would be killed by you, o gods, your approach when you kill him hould be without looking back, not looking to the side, clash with the opponent, slap his left side, attack anew his right side, cut down his snout, split his skull, rip open his belly, stretch out his intestines, draw out his entrails, tear out his liver, without delay finish off, bring to an end his life. If he goes to the forest, may he be eaten up by the tiger, bitten by the snake, whirled round and round by divine wrath! If he goes to the field, may he be caught by thunderclap, may his head be torn off by demons, may he be eaten by Pamuṅvan giants! Unceasingly in his home all diseases torment him! Please you gods Kuśika, Garga, Metrī, Kuruṣya and Pātañjala, guardian of the North, guardian of the South, of the West, of the East, throw him in the air, tear him asunder (?) among all gods, throw him into the great ocean, drown him at the dam! May he be caught by the holy gods in the water! May he be pulled by sea-monsters! May he be snatched by the crocodile! May it be there that he dies, the lawless man who destroys the Paṅurumbigyan-freehold at Ālasantan. May he suffer misfortune among all devatas deceased ancestors! May he go to ruins, may be be engulfed in the Phīra (or Dhīra: ocean)! May he end up plunged into hell! May he be dropped in the Great Raurava! May he be cooked by the forces of Yama! May he be hammered seven times by the Kiṅkaras servant of Yama. Surely, when he is given shape, it will be a bad one. Surely he will suffer as long as he lives! May all types of pain be experienced by him! May all sorts of pain be undergone by him! Every detestable thing of rebirth is what he will become! May he smoulder without being extinguised! As fanned ash, thus will become the lawless man who destroys the Paṅurumbigyan-freehold at Ālasantan!
